  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the differences between RTGS and NEFT?",
  "response": "RTGS (Real-Time Gross Settlement) and NEFT (National Electronic Funds Transfer) are two primary systems for transferring funds electronically in India. Below are the main differences between them:\n\n1. **Settlement Speed**:\n   - **RTGS**: The transfer of funds happens in real-time and on a gross basis. This means that the transactions are processed individually throughout the working hours of the RTGS system without any netting.\n   - **NEFT**: Transfers are processed in batches, typically on an hourly basis. This means there might be some delay as transactions are not processed in real-time.\n\n2. **Minimum and Maximum Transaction Limit**:\n   - **RTGS**: There is usually a minimum limit for transactions, often Rs. 2 lakh, but no maximum limit. It is designed for high-value transactions.\n   - **NEFT**: There is no minimum transaction limit, and it can be used for any amount. The maximum limit is set by the bank's policy.\n\n3. **Timings**:\n   - **RTGS**: Operates during the working hours defined by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), typically from 7 AM to 6 PM on weekdays and 7 AM to 12 PM on Saturdays.\n   - **NEFT**: Initially, NEFT operated during specified hours, but as of December 2019, NEFT transactions can be done 24x7, 365 days a year.\n\n4. **Service Charges**:\n   - **RTGS**: Banks may charge higher fees for RTGS transactions due to the high-value nature of the service.\n   - **NEFT**: Service charges for NEFT transactions are generally lower compared to RTGS.\n\n5. **Transaction Security and Reliability**:\n   - Both RTGS and NEFT are considered secure and reliable modes of transferring funds. However, the real-time nature of RTGS makes it particularly robust for urgent transactions.\n\n6. **Usage**:\n   - **RTGS**: Mainly used for large, high-value transactions that need to be settled immediately.\n   - **NEFT**: Suitable for a wide range of transactions, including low-value transfers, making it more flexible for everyday banking needs.\n\n7. **Processing Mechanism**:\n   - **RTGS**: The transactions are processed continuously throughout the RTGS system's operational hours.\n   - **NEFT**: The transactions are processed in batches at specific intervals throughout the day.\n\nThese differences make RTGS and NEFT suitable for different types of financial requirements.",
